{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b9d0ec70-497f-4e7c-94fb-7b6aa51cd48f","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a built-in MAUI `ContentPage` property — you need platform-specific configuration. Here's what's likely missing:\n\n### iOS — Disable Safe Area Insets\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"false\"\n    NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\">\n    <Grid>\n        <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n### Android — Enable Edge-to-Edge\nAdd this in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnCreate((activity, _) =>\n        {\n            var window = activity.Window!;\n            window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n            window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n            AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false);\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n> **Note:** On Android 15+ (API 35), edge-to-edge is enforced by default, but you still need `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` for the content to actually draw behind the bars.\n\n### Checklist\n- `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"false\"` — lets content extend behind notch/home indicator\n- `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(..., false)` — lets content draw behind Android system bars\n- `NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"` (or `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"`) — removes the app's nav bar\n- `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` on the `Image` — ensures it fills the space\n- No `Padding`/`Margin` on the page or parent layout","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"39e2b267-6c24-4f8b-923a-93e97178d17e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` but still have padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me check if there's relevant documentation or skill content in the repository that might help, but this seems like a general .NET MAUI knowledge question.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content:\n\n1. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the layout/view is one approach\n2. On Android, you need to handle the system bars explicitly\n\n\n3. On iOS, there's `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` that can be set to false to ignore safe area constraints\n\nI'm realizing the `SafeAreaEdges` property might not be a standard MAUI property, so the user may be working with a custom implementation or a different framework. The core approach in MAUI is using `IgnoreSafeArea` and platform-specific properties like the iOS `UseSafeArea` setting.\n\nFor Android, edge-to-edge mode needs to be enabled, especially in newer versions where it's enforced by default on Android 15+. The Image itself should have `AspectFill` to properly fill the space, and I need to check if there are any default padding or margin settings interfering with the full-screen layout, plus verify the NavigationPage configuration. the navigation bar using `HasNavigationBar=\"False\"` or `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"`, then disable safe area on iOS with `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"false\"`, and handle Android's edge-to-edge rendering through platform-specific configuration. The `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` property the user mentioned doesn't seem to be a standard MAUI API, so I should clarify the correct approach based on what's actually available in the framework. Setting up the XAML with the safe area disabled on iOS and hiding navigation bars, then configuring Android in the platform-specific code to handle edge-to-edge rendering...\n\nStill writing Android configuration...","outputTokens":2052,"requestId":"B800:2EAF75:100A2C7:141836E:69FFDAE7"},"id":"2afa648a-401e-4712-a55c-05b6b409440f","timestamp":"2026-0